{
  "texts": [
    "These real-space snapshots clearly reveal the emergence of the new Z q order.",
    "In the standard Z + q AFM ⊕ Z 2 NM phase, only one pair of states separated by π is visible, whereas in the Z - q AFM ⊕ Z 2 NM phase two distinct pairs of states appear, separated by ∆k = 1.",
    "In the long-wavelength limit this structure corresponds to effective half-integer clock states, with spin orientations at odd multiples of π/q.Our field-theoretical framework predicts that the phase with emergent Z - q degrees of freedom should persist for all finite even q > 4, with its extent expected to decrease as q increases, ultimately vanishing in the XY limit (q → ∞).",
    "The entanglement entropy (EE) patterns for q = 10 and q = 12 shown in Fig. 4(f) and (g) support this scenario, as the domain of the emergent phase indeed shrinks with increasing q.",
    "Nonetheless, our numerical analysis cannot completely rule out the possibility that the phase disappears at some large but finite q, rather than only in the strict XY limit.0 1 x sin( qϑ 2) cos( qϑ 2)T FIG. 6."
  ]
}